;
;Bolphor's book
INUMBER 1828
NAME 545
MISC
WEIGHT 5
VOLUME 3
ARTICLE A
IFPREVERB LOOK -1
	CLEARVERB
	ECHO PLAYER The tome is bound in leather, and the cover bears the words: My Journal, By Bolphor the Archmage
ENDIF
IFPREVERB READ -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 0
		ECHO PLAYER You will have to open it first.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 1
		ECHO PLAYER You read the first page:%cI am Bolphor, archmage of the first order, under the tutelage of Gala%cTanri, greatest mage in the world, and a truly wonderful woman.%cI have just begun my studies into the realms of metaphysical phenomenon,%cand am starting this journal so that future scholars might trace my life%cand my work.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 2
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 2:%cI have decided to study the field of other-dimensionial entities.%cGala seems somewhat uncertain, but is supportive. Things are going well,%cand for once, I am happy.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 3
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 3:%cI made a new friend today -- the aelfen Yoetra. She has been very nice,%cand seems interested in my work. She has offered to help me, but, though%cI could use an assistant, there is something about her that I just%cdo not trust. She did not seem offended by my refusal, and I hope we%cwill still be able to get along.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 4
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 4:%cI feel I am on the brink of something big here; I have, in the course%cof my research, discovered the existence of a group of very%cpowerful creatures known as the 'old ones'. They are vastly intelligent,%cand completely inhuman. My researches even suggest that it may have been%cone of them who caused the cataclysm. We will see.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 5
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 5:%cI am exited! As I have studied the old ones and their works, I see that%cit may actually be possible to summon one, and tap into its power!%cIf I can accomplish this, the benefits would be beyond calculation! I am%cso close, I can almost feel it... it is just beyond my grasp!
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 6
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 6:%cThose fools! To think I trusted them! I went to Gala and Yoetra with the%cnews of my discovery, and they spurned me, telling me my work was evil,%cthat the old ones would destroy Andor if I succeeded. How can they not%cunderstand? I would not summon them, unless I could control them%cas well. Fools, every one of them!
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 7
		ECHO PLAYER You read page 7:%cI am continuing my researches, in secret. The possible benefits are%ctoo great for me to stop now. I am too close, and I have gone too far%cto give up. If Gala and Yoetra cannot understand the benefits of my%cwork, then perhaps they will understand more once I am successful, and%cthey can see how I control the old ones.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 8
		ECHO PLAYER Defeat, right at my moment of triumph! I was only a day or two away from%cmy goal, when Yoetra discovered what I was up to. She has reported my%cactivities to Gala, and I have been thrown under house arrest, while they%cdiscuss my punishment. If only I could have made them understand. Well,%cwhat's done is done, and my fate is out of my hands now.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 9
		ECHO PLAYER They are going to exile me! And they are canny; they recognize that just%cabout anywhere they could send me, I could continue my work. So, they%care going to send me into the dark recesses of my own mind, with a%cmental block to prevent me from escaping. I don't know what I will do.%cToday is my last day on Andor.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 10
		ECHO PLAYER The writing on this page is very irregular:%cThe demons, and the shadows! They surround me, taunting me by their%cpresence. But I will show them. I will show them all! I WILL escape%cthis place, and I will have my revenge on those who trapped me here.%cYou will see... Yoetra, my day will come!
	ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB OPEN -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 ! 0
		ECHO PLAYER The tome is already open.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 0
		ECHO PLAYER You flip open the tome, revealing the first page.
		ECHO OTHERS %N flips the tome open to page one.
		EQUAL ITEMVAL2 1
	ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB CLOSE -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 0
		ECHO PLAYER The tome is already closed.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 ! 0
		ECHO PLAYER You close the tome.
		ECHO OTHERS %N closes the tome.
		EQUAL ITEMVAL2 0
	ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB FLIP -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 10
		ECHO PLAYER Having reached the end, you close the tome.
		EQUAL ITEMVAL3 1
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 0
		ECHO PLAYER You will have to open the tome before you can flip through the pages.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL2 < 10
		IFVAR ITEMVAL2 > 0
			ECHO PLAYER You flip to the next page.
			ECHO OTHERS %N flips to the next page.
			ADD ITEMVAL2 1
		ENDIF
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL3 = 1
		EQUAL ITEMVAL2 0
		EQUAL ITEMVAL3 0
	ENDIF
ENDIF
